06884nam a22013575i 9780691227863DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20221992nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021701051  a97806912278637 a10.1515/97806912278632doi  a(DE-B1597)576618  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN1993.5.R9 4aPN1993.5.R9b.H678 1992 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a384/.8/09471 aHorton, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Zero Hour :bGlasnost and Soviet Cinema in Transition /cAndrew Horton, Michael Brashinsky. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Period of Adjustment -- tPart One. Glasnost: Back To The Present -- t1. Back to the Present: (Representing the Soviet Past in Feature Films -- t2. "We Are Your Children": Soviet Youth, Cinema, and Changing Values -- t3. "Wherever Will I Begin?" Soviet Women in Cinema and on Film -- tPart Two. Glasnost: Down With Stuttering -- t4. Is It Easy to Be Honest? Glasnost in the Documentary Film -- t5. Down with Stuttering: Soviet Popular Genres and the New Film Language -- t6. From Accusatory to Joyful Laughter: Restructuring the Soviet Comic-Satiric Muse -- tPart Three. The Islands Of The Continent -- t7. The Islands of the Continent: A Revised Map for Ethnic Cinemas -- tIn Place of a Conclusion: The Zew Hour -- tFilmography -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNow faced with the "zero hour" created by a new freedom of expression and the dramatic breakup of the Soviet Union, Soviet cinema has recently become one of the most interesting in the world, aesthetically as well as politically. How have Soviet filmmakers responded to the challenges of glasnost? To answer this question, the American film scholar Andrew Horton and the Soviet critic Michael Brashinsky offer the first book-length study of the rapid changes in Soviet cinema that have been taking place since 1985. What emerges from their collaborative dialogue is not only a valuable work of film criticism but also a fascinating study of contemporary Soviet culture in general. Horton and Brashinsky examine a wide variety of films from BOMZH (initials standing for homeless drifter) through Taxi Blues and the glasnost blockbuster Little Vera to the Latvian documentary Is It Easy to Be Young? and the "new wave" productions of the "Wild Kazakh boys." The authors argue that the medium that once served the Party became a major catalyst for the deconstruction of socialism, especially through documentary filmmaking. Special attention is paid to how filmmakers from 1985 through 1990 represent the newly "discovered" past of the pre-glasnost era and how they depict troubled youth and conflicts over the role of women in society. The book also emphasizes the evolving uses of comedy and satire and the incorporation of "genre film" techniques into a new popular cinema. An intriguing discussion of films of Georgia, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, and Kazakhstan ends the work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCulture in motion pictures. 0aGlasnost. 0aMotion pictureszSoviet Union. 0aPopular culturezSoviet Union. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAfghan war.  aAgainst the Current.  aAlexander Nevsky.  aAmarcord.  aAuction (rock group).  aBallad of a Soldier.  aBattleship Potemkin.  aBeria Lavrenty.  aBrief Encounters.  aCapra, Frank.  aCarnival Night.  aChronicle of a Parade.  aCitizen Kane.  aCosmogony.  aDear Elena Sergeevna.  aDeath in Film.  aEar